Ari, Avram, Mendel, Moshe, Shraga, Aviva.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name from German <i>Gold</i>, Yiddish <i>gold</i> ‘gold’. In North America it is often a shortened form of one of the many compound artificial names of which <i>Gold</i> is the first element.","English and German: from Middle English <i>go(u)ld</i>, or Old English and Old High German <i>gold</i> ‘gold’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked in gold, i.e. a refiner, jeweler, or gilder, or as a nickname for someone who either had many gold possessions or bright yellow hair."]},{"name":"Goldinger","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Golding  ."]},{"name":"Colding","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Kristoffer.","Danish: probably a habitational name from Kolding. This wasoriginally the name of a river, from <i>kaldr</i> ‘cold’ + aderivational suffix <i>-ung</i>, hence ‘the cold river’.","English:perhaps a variant of   Golding  ."]},{"name":"Goulding","meanings":["English: variant of   Golding  .","Irish (Cork): adopted for <b>Mag Ualghairg</b>, see   McGoldrick  ."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (